events.description: Ashina Jiesheshuai and his tribesmen assaulted Emperor Taizong at Jiucheng Palace.

events.description: Pope Gregory II is elected.
events.html: • 715 – Pope Gregory II is elected.[1]

events.description: The Byzantine Empire reconquers Melitene under the leadership of John Kourkouas.
events.html: • 934 – The Byzantine Empire reconquers Melitene under the leadership of John Kourkouas.[2]

events.description: Henry I of France marries the Rus' princess, Anne of Kiev.
events.html: • 1051 – Henry I of France marries the Rus' princess, Anne of Kiev.[3]

events.description: John II of Castile defeats the Infantes of Aragon at the First Battle of Olmedo.
events.html: • 1445 – John II of Castile defeats the Infantes of Aragon at the First Battle of Olmedo.

events.description: Catherine of Aragon is married by proxy to Arthur, Prince of Wales. Catherine is 13 and Arthur is 12.
events.html: • 1499 – Catherine of Aragon is married by proxy to Arthur, Prince of Wales. Catherine is 13 and Arthur is 12.

events.description: French explorer Jacques Cartier sets sail on his second voyage to North America with three ships, 110 men, and Chief Donnacona's two sons (whom Cartier had kidnapped during his first voyage).
events.html: • 1535 – French explorer Jacques Cartier sets sail on his second voyage to North America with three ships, 110 men, and Chief Donnacona's two sons (whom Cartier had kidnapped during his first voyage).

events.description: Anne Boleyn, the second wife of Henry VIII of England, is beheaded for adultery, treason, and incest.
events.html: • 1536 – Anne Boleyn, the second wife of Henry VIII of England, is beheaded for adultery, treason, and incest.

events.description: The Prome Kingdom falls to the Taungoo Dynasty in present-day Myanmar.
events.html: • 1542 – The Prome Kingdom falls to the Taungoo Dynasty in present-day Myanmar.

events.description: Thirty Years' War: French forces under the duc d'Enghien decisively defeat Spanish forces at the Battle of Rocroi, marking the symbolic end of Spain as a dominant land power.
events.html: • 1643 – Thirty Years' War: French forces under the duc d'Enghien decisively defeat Spanish forces at the Battle of Rocroi, marking the symbolic end of Spain as a dominant land power.

events.description: An Act of Parliament declaring England a Commonwealth is passed by the Long Parliament. England would be a republic for the next eleven years.
events.html: • 1649 – An Act of Parliament declaring England a Commonwealth is passed by the Long Parliament. England would be a republic for the next eleven years.

events.description: The Invasion of Jamaica begins during the Anglo-Spanish War.
events.html: • 1655 – The Invasion of Jamaica begins during the Anglo-Spanish War.

events.description: Jean-Pierre Christin developed the centigrade temperature scale.
events.html: • 1743 – Jean-Pierre Christin developed the centigrade temperature scale.

events.description: King George II of Great Britain grants the Ohio Company a charter of land around the forks of the Ohio River.
events.html: • 1749 – King George II of Great Britain grants the Ohio Company a charter of land around the forks of the Ohio River.

events.description: American Revolutionary War: A Continental Army garrison surrenders in the Battle of The Cedars.
events.html: • 1776 – American Revolutionary War: A Continental Army garrison surrenders in the Battle of The Cedars.

events.description: New England's Dark Day, an unusual darkening of the day sky, was observed over the New England states and parts of Canada.
events.html: • 1780 – New England's Dark Day, an unusual darkening of the day sky, was observed over the New England states and parts of Canada.

events.description: Napoleon Bonaparte founds the Legion of Honour.
events.html: • 1802 – Napoleon Bonaparte founds the Legion of Honour.

events.description: U.S. President John Quincy Adams signs the Tariff of 1828 into law, protecting wool manufacturers in the United States.
events.html: • 1828 – U.S. President John Quincy Adams signs the Tariff of 1828 into law, protecting wool manufacturers in the United States.

events.description: Captain Sir John Franklin and his ill-fated Arctic expedition depart from Greenhithe, England.
events.html: • 1845 – Captain Sir John Franklin and his ill-fated Arctic expedition depart from Greenhithe, England.

events.description: Mexican–American War: Mexico ratifies the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo thus ending the war and ceding California, Nevada, Utah and parts of four other modern-day U.S. states to the United States for US$15 million.
events.html: • 1848 – Mexican–American War: Mexico ratifies the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo thus ending the war and ceding California, Nevada, Utah and parts of four other modern-day U.S. states to the United States for US$15 million.

events.description: Buffalo Bill's first Buffalo Bill's Wild West opens in Omaha, Nebraska.
events.html: • 1883 – Buffalo Bill's first Buffalo Bill's Wild West opens in Omaha, Nebraska.[4]

events.description: Great Britain annexes Tonga Island.
events.html: • 1900 – Great Britain annexes Tonga Island.[5]

events.description: Second Boer War: British troops relieve Mafeking.
events.html: • 1900 – Second Boer War: British troops relieve Mafeking.

events.description: Parks Canada, the world's first national park service, is established as the Dominion Parks Branch under the Department of the Interior.
events.html: • 1911 – Parks Canada, the world's first national park service, is established as the Dominion Parks Branch under the Department of the Interior.

events.description: The Norwegian football club Rosenborg BK is founded.
events.html: • 1917 – The Norwegian football club Rosenborg BK is founded.

events.description: Mustafa Kemal Atatürk lands at Samsun on the Anatolian Black Sea coast, initiating what is later termed the Turkish War of Independence.
events.html: • 1919 – Mustafa Kemal Atatürk lands at Samsun on the Anatolian Black Sea coast, initiating what is later termed the Turkish War of Independence.

events.description: The United States Congress passes the Emergency Quota Act establishing national quotas on immigration.

events.description: Finnish cavalry general C. G. E. Mannerheim is appointed the field marshal.

events.description: Zveno and the Bulgarian Army engineer a coup d'état and install Kimon Georgiev as the new Prime Minister of Bulgaria.

events.description: World War II: In the aftermath of the Battle of the Coral Sea, Task Force 16 heads to Pearl Harbor for repairs.

events.description: Winston Churchill's second wartime address to the U.S. Congress

events.description: Syrian demonstrators in Damascus are fired upon by French troops injuring twelve, leading to the Levant Crisis.
events.html: • 1945 – Syrian demonstrators in Damascus are fired upon by French troops injuring twelve, leading to the Levant Crisis.[8]

events.description: A barge containing munitions destined for Pakistan explodes in the harbor at South Amboy, New Jersey, devastating the city.
events.html: • 1950 – A barge containing munitions destined for Pakistan explodes in the harbor at South Amboy, New Jersey, devastating the city.

events.description: Egypt announces that the Suez Canal is closed to Israeli ships and commerce.
events.html: • 1950 – Egypt announces that the Suez Canal is closed to Israeli ships and commerce.

events.description: The North Vietnamese Army establishes Group 559, whose responsibility is to determine how to maintain supply lines to South Vietnam; the resulting route is the Ho Chi Minh trail.

events.description: Venera program: Venera 1 becomes the first man-made object to fly by another planet by passing Venus (the probe had lost contact with Earth a month earlier and did not send back any data).

events.html: • 1961 – At Silchar Railway Station, Assam, 11 Bengalis die when police open fire on protesters demanding state recognition of Bengali language in the Bengali Language Movement.

events.description: A birthday salute to U.S. President John F. Kennedy takes place at Madison Square Garden, New York City. The highlight is Marilyn Monroe's rendition of "Happy Birthday".
events.html: • 1962 – A birthday salute to U.S. President John F. Kennedy takes place at Madison Square Garden, New York City. The highlight is Marilyn Monroe's rendition of "Happy Birthday".
